He was not called Sylla because of Hellenism but because an ancestor instituted the Games of Apollo into Rome's festivals after consulting the SIbylline books, thus some say that the name Sulla originated from this. Others support the claim that the son of Publius Cornelius Rufius, the banished dictator, received the name Sulla deriving from Latin "Sura": (feminine) calf of the leg. To avoid confusion, the latter is more frequently used.
